<Author>tanseaway
<Content>A wonderful example of the best of Ritz-Carlton Just stayed at the Ritz-Carlton Tokyo a few days ago on vacation in Tokyo. It's one of a group of new ultra-luxury hotels above Tokyo's traditional 5-star stalwarts (i.e. the Imperial hotel and its ilk) that have opened in recent years. It's quite new - it just opened last year. Its location is excellent - it is part of the Tokyo Midtown complex, which includes a swanky shopping centre. Midtown is in Roppongi, Tokyo's entertainment district for foreigners and expat types. The Roppongi subway station is connected to Midtown by underground passages - approximately a 5-minute walk from the hotel.Reception staff at check-in were courteous as only the Japanese can be, and efficient. The concierge staff were very helpful and knowledgeable. All front desk staff spoke excellent English.Hotel decor is typical of Ritz-Carlton hotels - both in the lobby and in the rooms. Lots of wood and some classic details. Zen and modern it is not. The rooms are huge and the view of the city was fantastic as the hotel starts from Level 45 of an office tower. Cleanliness was utterly impeccable - as one would expect of a Japanese hotel. The beds were superb. Bathrooms had separate shower stalls and rain showers. Of course, typical Japanese standards of service were found in every corner of the hotel - i.e. attentive and courteous beyond what one might encounter outside Japan. In conclusion, this hotel is costly, but it delivers in spades. If you can bite the bullet, this hotel is a fabulous choice. 
