<Content>The best in Tokyo I have stayed at all the main competitors; Park Hyatt, Grand Hyatt, Mandarin, Peninsula, Four Seasons, etc. These are all very good hotels but I think the Ritz-Carlton is now the best, its my favourite anyway. The Tokyo Midtown development sets an example to the rest of the world on how to successfully combine shops, offices, cafe/restuarants. And on top you have the Ritz-Carlton hotel with the most amazing views above Tokyo. Location: if you have business in Akasaka area then the location is fine, if however your business is in Marunouchi then you're looking at a 30mins taxi ride; for this area the Peninsula is best located (and to a degree the Mandarin). At night you will be happy that you are staying at the Ritz-Carlton as you can just stumble back from Roppongi... it's just a 5mins walk from the roppongi crossingRoom: the Millenia suite is big with its own living area. It feels generously spaced to give that extra luxury feeling. Excellent bathroom. But the views! The panorama is just breathtaking. I spent one very early morning (jetlagged) watching the sunrise over tokyo, very memorable. Service: Very good as you would expect. I treated myself to the rolls-royce transfer to and from the airport - which was fantastic. I left something valuable in my room (my watch) and only realised when we got to the airport. The hotel mailed it to me and i got it safe and sound a few days later. 
